The inhibitory behavior of C-Dots across a time scale of 0.5–48 h was investigated by conducting EIS measurements for steel electrodes in 1 M HCl in the presence and absence of 200 mg L−1 of each analyzed C-Dots (Fig. 7
                        ). The results showed that the semicircle diameter and impedance modulus of the steel electrode immersed in 1 M HCl decreased over time, indicating a faster corrosion rate (Fig. 7a). However, in the presence of C-Dots, the rate of the corrosion process was reduced, resulting in an increase in the charge transfer resistance (R

                           ct
                        ) at the metal/solution interface. This increase in R

                           ct
                         led to an improvement in the inhibitive efficiency of C-Dots, as shown in Fig. 7a-f and Table 3S (ESM).
